references:
How to mask or partially mask an attribute depends on the attribute’s type.
There are four types: fixed length string, variable length string, date, and categorical.
For example, for variable string attributes such as a person’s name, the masked and partially masked value is calculated by Damerau-Levenshtein distance, which allows insertions, deletions, substitutions, and transposition.
For date attributes such as “DoB” (Date of Birth), masked and partially disclosed modes include inter and intra element discrepancies between year, month, and day.
Table 1 shows some examples of partially disclosed value for different types of attributes.

Let X𝑋X be a data set with N𝑁N records and D𝐷D non-sensitive attributes, containing potential pairs of records to be linked. A partial display 𝒳𝒳\mathcal{X} is a set of 2​n2𝑛2n rows and D𝐷D attributes obtained from n≤(N2)𝑛binomial𝑁2n\leq\binom{N}{2} pairs of records from X𝑋X that are displayed to a user performing interactive record linkage. The rows in 𝒳𝒳\mathcal{X} are many-to-one related to the records in X𝑋X. The values of the attributes in 𝒳𝒳\mathcal{X} may be fully disclosed, partially disclosed or masked versions of the corresponding attributes in X𝑋X, as described in Table 1.

references: We illustrate the utility of KAPR via an example. Consider Table 2, containing microdata about individual people, whose schema comprises the identifier {Name}Name\left\{\texttt{Name}\right\}, the quasi-identifiers {DOB,Race}DOBRace\left\{\texttt{DOB},~{}\texttt{Race}\right\}, and the sensitive attribute {Income}Income\left\{\texttt{Income}\right\}. The data linkage task to be accomplished is to merge duplicate records in this data set. This is accomplished by having a worker manually inspect all pairs of similar records and decide whether or not they correspond to the same individual. In this example, the ground truth is that records 1 and 2 belong to unique individuals, while records 3 and 4 correspond to the same individual (as indicated by the row colors). Because all of the records in this table are quite similar, the user interface will display every possible pair of records from this table to the worker.

Initially, the pairs will be displayed in masked mode. This corresponds to the information disclosure state depicted in Table 5. The field ID contains a tuple denoting which records from the base data set (Table 2) constitute this pair, and the field i𝑖i is used to label the rows of data displayed. Since Income is a sensitive attribute, it will not be displayed. We denote by 𝐩isubscript𝐩𝑖\mathbf{p}_{i} the vector whose entries consist of the proportions of characters of the Name, DOB and Race fields respectively. We denote by kisubscript𝑘𝑖k_{i} the size of the anonymity set for record i𝑖i. In principle, any number of the characters of Name and DOB can be disclosed. Because Race is a Category variable, it can only be not disclosed or fully disclosed; there is no option for partial disclosure. In this mode, each row i𝑖i in the display has an anonymity set size of ki=4subscript𝑘𝑖4k_{i}=4, because the masked data could correspond to any of the records in Table 2. However, no characters of any of the three attributes are disclosed, meaning 𝐩i=(0,0,0)subscript𝐩𝑖000\mathbf{p}_{i}=(0,0,0) for each row i𝑖i, and hence Ki=0subscript𝐾𝑖0K_{i}=0 for each row as well. Thus, the KAPR score for this information disclosure state is 0.

The incremental display allows the user to reveal incremental additional information about any cell in the display, and the privacy cost of this action is quantified by the amount by which the KAPR score is incremented as result. As an example, the user may have decided to switch from masked mode to partial mode for every cell in the display, as depicted in Table 5. This will change the values of kisubscript𝑘𝑖k_{i} and 𝐩isubscript𝐩𝑖\mathbf{p}_{i} for each row. For example, for row i=1𝑖1i=1, the size of the anonymity set kisubscript𝑘𝑖k_{i} has decreased from 4 in masked mode to 3 in partial mode, since we now know that the last character of Name is ‘y’, which means it must correspond to one of the three rows where Name = ‘Mary’ in Table 2. Furthermore, we have now revealed 1/4141/4 of the characters of Name, but still no characters of the other attributes, meaning 𝐩i=(1/4,0,0)subscript𝐩𝑖1400\mathbf{p}_{i}=(1/4,0,0) now. In this case, since N=12𝑁12N=12, D=3𝐷3D=3, this means that Ki=1/432subscript𝐾𝑖1432K_{i}=1/432. The value of Kisubscript𝐾𝑖K_{i} for each row is shown separately; for i∈{11,12}𝑖1112i\in\{11,12\}, Ki=0subscript𝐾𝑖0K_{i}=0 still, because the identifying attributes of the underlying records are identical, and thus no characters need be revealed. The KAPR score for this information disclosure state is ∑i=112Ki=31/432≈0.072>0superscriptsubscript𝑖112subscript𝐾𝑖314320.0720\sum_{i=1}^{12}K_{i}=31/432\approx 0.072>0. So the KAPR score has increased incrementally from 00 when every row was displayed in masked mode. It should be clear from the example that the KAPR score for this information disclosure state does not depend upon the order in which the information was disclosed; regardless of the order in which the user clicked the cells of the display to reveal more information, the final information disclosure state is the same, and the KAPR score depends only on the information disclosure state.
